    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-01-17T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-01-17T05:00:00-05:00" n="937"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d937">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/1–1746: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Robertson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-01-17T17:00:00+07:00"
                            >January 17, 1946—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received January 18—9:47 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>124. By telegram dated January 14 Ward informs Embassy that Chiang Ching-kuo left
                    Tihwa for Chungking Jan 13. (Sent to Dept, repeated Moscow as 16.) Ward says
                    Chiang is understood to share conviction that first prerequisite for peace is
                    clean sweep of present provincial regime.</p>
                <closer>For Chargé: <lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Smyth</hi>
                    </signed>
                    <note n="9" xml:id="d937fn9">Robert L. Smyth, Counselor of Embassy in
                        China.</note>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
